<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Received by Walesa </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401114994 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1030 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 14 Jan--On Friday morning, President Lech 
Walesa received Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky, who 
is on an official visit to Poland. 
  Welcoming the guest, the president said that it is important 
for Poland and Hungary to speak up on issues that are important 
for Europe because "others can do something for us and without 
us [as received]." 
  In Walesa's opinion, both countries should maintain working 
contacts "in the context" of the situation in Europe, "which 
determines our security and prosperity." Walesa said that the 
Partnership for Peace proposal can be a considerable partnership 
if "we decide about its shape ourselves." He added that the 
gifts are nice but do not always "suit our appetite." 
  Minister Jeszenszky stated that decisions made in Brussels 
and Prague "would not have been as significant without the work 
of Poland and the Polish president." He added that it is 
important to keep U.S. and West European politicians to their 
word and ensure that they fulfill their promises. "We have 
reasons to hope, but we also have reasons to be concerned," 
Jeszenszky said. 

</TEXT>

