<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Hoping for `Influx' of U.S. Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301190394 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1301190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Silviya Velikova] </F>
  [Text] Today Madeleine Albright, U.S. permanent 
representative at the United Nations, who arrived in Bulgaria 
today, was received, respectively, by President of the Republic 
Zhelyu Zhelev and Prime Minister Lyuben Berov. Ms. Albright 
briefed them on the U.S. Partnership for Peace Initiative, which 
has already been adopted by NATO. 
  Ms. Albright expressed the U.S. expectation that Bulgaria 
will also be one of the East European states to join in this 
initiative. Ms. Albright voiced the U.S. Administration's 
willingness to continue to provide economic assistance to the 
countries of Central and Eastern Europe. According to her, the 
financing of infrastructure projects, mainly in the 
transportation and communications fields, will be of particular 
importance for Bulgaria. 
  Dr. Zhelev confirmed his insistent invitation to President 
Bill Clinton to visit Bulgaria. 
  At both meetings, discussions were held on Yugoslav crisis 
issues and the sanctions imposed on Serbia and Montenegro. 
President Zhelev expressed the view that certain indirect 
measures are already in hand to alleviate the losses that 
Bulgaria is suffering from observing the Yugoslav embargo, but 
we hope to obtain even better trade possibilities with the 
United States and to see an influx of new U.S. investments into 
Bulgaria. 

</TEXT>

