<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Granic Warns of Intensified War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701193694 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by unidentified correspondent in Geneva] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Correspondent] On one side we have Croatia's 
efforts for peace and a call for peace by the European Union, 
and on the other side the Muslims are maneuvering with the war 
option and the display of force. [passage omitted] 
  Late this afternoon Minister Granic held talks with Haris 
Silajdzic. 
  [Begin Granic recording] "The European Union has sent a 
(?memorandum) in which it warns all the sides to make all 
possible efforts to achieve an urgent end to hostilities and an 
agreement. This is probably one of the most important days of 
the Geneva negotiations. If no agreement is reached, there is a 
big chance that the war will intensify even further. 
  Croatia is making extreme efforts to bring about an end to 
the conflict and, in the spirit of the agreement that President 
Tudjman proposed to President Izetbegovic, primarily an end to 
the conflict between the Croats and the Muslims, and to reach an 
agreement between them. Croatia is also making efforts to 
normalize relations between Croatia and Serbia on the basis of 
mutual recognition and of certain necessary preconditions. That 
was the main topic of all the talks today, the lengthy talks 
with Prime Minister Silajdzic and with the Bosnian Muslim 
delegation." [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

