<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Secret' Antiterror Accord Signed With Turkey </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1501170894 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1600 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1501170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, Jan. 15 (A.A) -- Turkey and Bulgaria will 
take joint action against terrorism. Bulgarian anti-terror 
department director Feodor Vladimirov told AA that they have met 
with Turkish officials in July and have signed a cooperation 
protocol against international terror organizations. He added 
that the matter had been kept in secret so far, for security 
reasons. 
  During the meeting Turkish officials briefed their Bulgarian 
colleagues on the terror organization in Turkey and gave 
detailed information on the connections of these in Europe. 
Vladimirov said that Bulgaria was being used as a bridge in 
drug and arms smuggling. 
  "We also know that some separatist terrorists are 
temporarily 
staying in Bulgaria when they flee to Europe. However, terror 
groups are not using Bulgaria as a shelter," he said. 

</TEXT>

