<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   BSP, SDS Blamed for `Political Tension' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1501145894 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 2000 
GMT 14 Jan 93 </F>

<F P=103> AU1501145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The BSP [Bulgarian Socialist Party] and SDS [Union 
of Democratic Forces] are responsible for again creating a 
situation of political tension, states a memorandum adopted this 
evening at a special session of the Council for Cooperation. 
  According to the members of the council, what is needed is 
for all the political forces in the country to rally around the 
national priorities. According to the memorandum, parliament 
must speed up its work on establishing the legislative basis for 
regulating the political, economic, and social reforms in 
Bulgaria. The government should adopt severe measures to bring 
the crime rate under control, eliminate crime, and speed up the 
economic and agricultural reforms. The president should 
consolidate his role as head of state and the personification of 
the unity of the nation, as stated in the Constitution. 
  The memorandum is signed by 10 of the 11 parties that are 
members of the Council for Cooperation. 

</TEXT>

