<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister on Russian Role in Security System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701193894 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1800 
GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tomorrow the Polish Government will adopt a final 
view on Poland's participation in the American Partnership for 
Peace program. During U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to 
Russia, Boris Yeltsin came out for Russia's full participation 
in the program. According to President Yeltsin, it is possible 
for Russia to join NATO, but only together with all former 
allies of the East Bloc. 
  We asked Defense Minister Piotr Kolodziejczyk whether 
possible access to NATO by Russia would not undermine Western 
security guarantees to our country. 
  [Begin Kolodziejczyk recording] Nobody is going to give full 
guarantees. We have to strive after them, this is obvious. The 
statements by President Yeltsin, however, well, they vary in 
tone and they are not always consistent. 
  Still, I think that Clinton achieved a lot. If Yeltsin 
accepts the participation in the Partnership for Peace, it means 
that we can feel a little safer -- if these intentions are 
genuine. No security system without Russia or, even worse, 
against Russia would be either permanent or safe. That is why I 
receive the statement favorably. We will see how it is going to 
look in practice. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

