<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs To Respond to Muslim Rejection of Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701162094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1510 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 17 Jan (TANJUG) -- The [Bosnian Serb] 
assembly will discuss the latest situation created after the 
Muslims rejected the plan which offers them 33.3 percent of 
[Bosnian] territory and a "reasonable way to gain access to the 
river Sava, and we now have to see which way to proceed now", 
Republic of Srpska [RS] president Radovan Karadzic told TANJUG 
today. 
  According to him, the Muslim representatives rejected the 
33.3 percent of the territory offered to them -- the percentage 
the international community has insisted on -- in the talks 
Bosnian Serb assembly president Momcilo Krajisnik held with them 
at Sarajevo airport on Saturday [16 January]. 
  "The most important thing is that we met the demand by the 
international community, which requested 30 percent. The 
Muslims then demanded 33 percent. The international community 
supported that demand. We found even the additional 3 percent, 
and then the Muslims rejected that too," Karadzic recalled 
before today's session of the Bosnian Serb assembly in Bijeljina. 
  "The war is still going on. People are still getting killed, 
and we have made many concessions precisely to end the war and 
the killing and to have peace immediately," the RS president 
said. "Since this has not happened, we have to decide today 
which path to take in the future." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49800 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu011_i_94004" </HT>


