<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koljevic Announces New Platform for Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1701213894 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2100 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1701213894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] This evening, the assembly of the republic of 
Srpska meeting in Bijeljina ended its discussion on the platform 
of the Serbian delegation for the peace talks in Geneva tomorrow 
[18 January]. At the end of the session, Nikola Koljevic, vice 
president of the republic of Srpska, made a statement for 
Belgrade Radio's special correspondent Milorad Denda: 
  [Denda] Professor Koljevic, what did today's session of the 
assembly of the Serbian Republic conclude? 
  [Koljevic] Today's session on the platform for the peace 
agreement concluded that the delegation of the republic of 
Srpska will once again offer in Geneva what the Serbian side has 
been asked to offer in the past, namely territorial concessions, 
and the administration of the district of Sarajevo, under 
specific conditions agreed upon during the negotiations. 
However, considering the public statements by the Sarajevo 
Presidency, especially by Messrs. Izetbegovic and Ganic, the 
assembly has adopted another platform in case the Muslim side 
does not accept the proffered peace agreement. 
  This platform will be revealed, that is presented, in Geneva 
tomorrow, and the general conclusion, if I may say so, is 
unanimous and undivided that if the Muslim side does not want 
the agreement on these bases, the representatives of the 
republic of Srpska will take a very specific and definitive 
stand that will lead toward the affirmation of the republic of 
Srpska on completely new bases. 
  [Denda] Can you be more specific about these new bases? 
  [Koljevic] These bases will be discussed, or rather the 
platform itself deals with these bases. The most important 
element for these bases is that we will proceed with the demand 
for a cease-fire and the de facto situation on the ground. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49801 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu011_i_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-011 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

