<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic Discusses Meeting With Krajisnik </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501200594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1501200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] After a month's break, 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic had a meeting 
with Momcilo Krajisnik [president of the Bosnian Serb assembly] 
at Sarajevo airport. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent] Mr Prime Minister, which 
issues did you discuss today? 
  [Silajdzic] We discussed political issues, electricity and 
gas supplies and prisoner exchanges. 
  [Correspondent] What did you agree to? 
  [Silajdzic] Let us begin with easier issues. Concerning 
electricity supply, we agreed to repair the power line between 
Sarajevo and Buca Potok. Repair teams have tried to go out to 
do the repairs four times, but the Serb side did not allow them 
to do anything. However, it was said this time that they would 
allow it. We will see. 
  It is important for both sides to respect their mutual 
interests [words indistinct]. Concerning the exchange of 
prisoners, the big problem is that we are not sure that the 
number of prisoners registered by the Red Cross is correct. We 
think that there are prisoners [words indistinct] 
  Therefore, I think that a partial exchange of prisoners is 
possible, which means that we will exchange as many prisoners as 
possible, but that an exchange according to the all-for-all 
principle -- according to Red Cross lists -- is not possible for 
the time being because we think that this would not be an 
all-for-all exchange. We believe that the Red Cross has not 
registered all prisoners. 
  The gas supplies were interrupted yesterday. I hope that we 
solved that problem too, and that this will not happen in the 
future. 
  Concerning political issues, I must say that we met after a 
long time, but there are no results, no changes. Our positions 
have remained unchanged. We will meet in Geneva soon. I cannot 
say whether any progress will be made there. Both sides want 
peace, at least judging by statements. However, we do not want 
the peace which is being offered to us, which is unacceptable. 
I do not know whether any progress in that respect will be 
made. I also must say that our side stressed the problem of 
bombing the city [Sarajevo], and the actions taken despite 
promises that they would not be taken in other parts of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. However, I must say that the other side 
voiced the same complaints concerning the territories under 
occupation. [passage indistinct] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

