<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Orders Ban on Attacks on UNPROFOR </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701154594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1428 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, 17 Jan (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the republic of Srpska, today issue an order to all 
subordinate commands and members of the republic of Srpska army 
strictly to refrain, as always before, from engaging in any 
military activities against UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] and 
other international organizations. 
  The order, issued ahead of the new round of Geneva 
negotiations on former Bosnia-Herzegovina, is one more measure 
of precaution in order to reduce to the minimum possible 
manipulations, imputations, and accusations at the expense of 
the republic of Srpska army, that it allegedly imperils members 
of the international organizations in former Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
sources close to the republic of Srpska leadership believe. 
  The Serbian side has so far been exceptionally cooperative 
with international organizations, but it has often been accused 
of putting humanitarian missions in jeopardy, despite the fact 
that it has never engaged in military actions against members of 
the international organizations, the sources say. [passage 
omitted] 
  With a view to preventing any undesirable incidents with 
international organizations, Karadzic issued a strict ban on all 
military activities in the direction of Sarajevo airport 
directed against any aircraft landing at the airport, any points 
of deployment and convoys belonging to UNPROFOR, the UNHCR, the 
International Committee of the Red Cross, and other humanitarian 
organizations. 
  President Karadzic ordered that all UNPROFOR convoys, 
military observers, and convoys belonging to international 
humanitarian organizations, that have obtained valid permission 
to move around in the territory of the republic of Srpska, be 
provided with full protection and unhindered movement, with 
planned and necessary inspection, and that "a completely fair 
and professional attitude" be taken toward representatives of 
all these organizations. 
  He also ordered that all controversial issues arising with 
UNPROFOR representatives and military observers be dealt with 
exclusively through corps commands and the main headquarters of 
the republic of Srpska army, while disputes with international 
humanitarian organizations are to be dealt with through the 
government's coordinating body, a statement dispatched from the 
office of republic of Srpska president Radovan Karadzic says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

