<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prlic: Bosnian Croats To Join Croatia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401205294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1723 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Jan 14 (TANJUG) -- Prime minister of the 
Croatian republic of Herceg-Bosna Jadranko Prlic said that the 
Bosnian Croat state will join neighbouring Croatia if the former 
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina breaks up. 
  In a statement to the Split weekly NEDELJNA DALMACIJA Prlic 
said that Bosnia-Herzegovina can only survive as a union of the 
republics of the three constituent nations -- Moslems Serbs and 
Croats, and that if such a state is formed Herceg-Bosna would 
not secede. Asked if Herceg-Bosna and the republic of Bosnian 
Serbs (RS) would recognize each other Prlic said that this would 
automatically take place if the union is formed for it provides 
for the existence of three mutually recognized republics. 
  Even though the Bosnian Croats and the Bosnian Serbs assured 
one third of the territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina the Moslems 
asked for at the last round of peace talks in Geneva and 
Brussels last month, the Moslems again turned down the plan 
saying that they were dissatisfied with the quality of the 
territories. 
  What the Bosnian Moslem leadership wants is a 
Moslem-dominated unitary Bosnia-Herzegovina, which was confirmed 
Wednesday by Bosnian Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic who said 
that the Moslems have to fight for a united Bosnia and the 
preservation of Islam there and called for new military 
operations. He also stressed that his troops were now 200,000 
strong and that things were now different. 
  The war in Bosnia-Herzegovina broke out in April 1992 
because 
Izetbegovic insisted on a unitary state, which was first 
rejected by the Bosnian Serbs and later by the Bosnian Croats, 
who declared their own states within the former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

