Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Zagreb, Jan 15 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Croat 
commander General Ante Roso said on Saturday [15 January] he had 
ordered his troops to bomb, if neccesary, the explosives factory 
in Vitez which has been the target of fierce Moslem attacks in 
the pasts few days. Vowing not to allow the enemy to take 
control of the factory, General Roso said in a statement 
broadcast on Zagreb television that the Moslems were fiercely 
attacking Vitez and Novi Travnik, but that the local Croat 
troops were successfully yielding [as received] to the pressure. 
  Commenting on the situation in central Bosnia, he said the 
fiercest Croat-Moslem fighting had been reported in the Lasva 
river valley. 
  The Bosnian Croat commander also said he had not accepted or 
signed any ceasefire at the latest round of talks with Bosnian 
Moslem commander Rasim Delic, noting that comprehensive 
political documents were needed for such an agreement. [passage 
