<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic's Forces Seek To Arrest Abdic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401201594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1843 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Petrovac, Jan 14 (TANJUG) -- Fierce intra-Moslem 
clashes between forces of the radical Bosnian Moslem leader 
Alija Izetbegovic and his rival Fikret Abdic continue Friday [14 
January] on all fronts in western Bosnia while Izetbegovic 
terrorist groups are trying lo arrest Abdic. 
  Under Abdic's leadership Moslems from the Cazin Krajina 
declared the autonomous province of western Bosnia in September 
last year in defiance of Izetbegovic's war option. They urged 
for the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina, which broke out in April 
1992, to be solved through negotiations with Bosnian Serbs and 
Bosnian Croats with whom Abdic signed seperate peace accords. 
The fiercest fighting is reported by local Moslem media of the 
Cazin Krajina to be going on around Trsce and Trzacka Rastela, 
places taken three days ago by the Abdic forces. 
  The autonomous province agency ZBIA reports that Izetbegovic 
forces have launched an all-out attack but that they cannot 
penetrate the lines held by the Abdic forces and have therefore 
sent several sabotage and terrorist groups to try to get into 
Velika Kladusa, the political center of the province, and arrest 
Abdic. 
  The agency reports that one of the groups was eliminated in 
the vicinity of Todorovo, by Velika Kladusa. 

</TEXT>

