<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG Notes Clinton Remarks on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501114694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1104 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1501114694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Clinton: Sending of Troops to Bosnia Would be Sheer Folly" </F>
-- TANJUG headline] 
  [Text] Moscow, January 15 (TANJUG) -- United States (U.S.) 
President Bill Clinton has said that his country was not sending 
troops to the former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
nor did it want to seize territories, because that would be 
sheer folly. 
  A civil war of its three constitutive peoples -- Moslems, 
Serbs and Croats -- has been raging in Bosnia-Herzegovina since 
April 1992. 
  Clinton on Friday evening [14 January] told Russian 
television that the U.S. supported Bosnian Moslems because it 
supports the multi-national government of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
which is recognized by the United Nations. Clinton, however, 
immediately added that his country knew that the Bosnian 
Government included mostly Moslem elements. The U.S. supports 
the U.N. mission and wants the bloodshed of people in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to end, the U.S. President said. 
  There are no more legally elected representatives of Bosnian 
Serbs or Bosnian Croats in the authorities of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. They walked out of all legal organs because 
Bosnian Moslems, violating the constitutionally established 
equality of the three peoples, want to enforce their domination. 
  The Serbs were the first to leave the Bosnian leadership 
because the Moslem-Croat authorities asked for the recognition 
of the independence of Bosnia-Herzegovina without their 
approval, although the Constitution specifically said that major 
decisions can be adopted only on the grounds of consensus among 
the three peoples. Disagreeing with the insistence of Bosnian 
Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic on a unitary Bosnia-Herzegovina 
in which his fellow Moslems and Islam would dominate, Bosnian 
Serbs and Bosnian Croats have proclaimed their own state 
communities -- the Serb republic and the Croatian republic of 
Herzeg-Bosna, respectively. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49823 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu011_y_94004" </HT>


