<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Army Chief of Staff Ends Visit, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701140694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1213 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 17 Jan (TANJUG) -- The Macedonian press 
today quotes a statement by the U.S. Army Chief of Staff General 
Gordon Sullivan that the American Army is ready to prevent any 
aggression against (the former Yugoslav Republic of) Macedonia 
and to provide humanitarian aid for Macedonia. 
  Gen. Gordon yesterday spent several hours in Macedonia and 
visited American soldiers with UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] 
and two blue helmet observer positions. Before his departure 
from Skopje he said that he was very satisfied with UNPROFOR's 
mission on preserving stability in "this important region." The 
U.S. Army Chief of Staff ruled out the possibility of increasing 
the contingent of U.S. soldiers with UNPROFOR stationed in 
Macedonia. Asked what his opinion was about a possible NATO 
military intervention in the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, he 
briefly said that he was a soldier, not a diplomat. Gen. 
Sullivan also had a meeting in Skopje with the chief of general 
staff of the Macedonian army, Colonel-General Dragoljub Bocinov. 

</TEXT>

