<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rugova Welcomes NATO's Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401135094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1301 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1401135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, 14 Jan (TANJUG) -- Ibrahim Rugova, 
president of the Democratic Alliance of Kosovo (DSK), today 
welcomed the NATO decision on partnership with eastern European 
countries made at the summit in Brussels. At a news conference, 
he did not comment on the NATO threat to bomb the Bosnian Serb 
positions, but only said that "the threat is realistic." The 
DSK leader described as positive British Prime Minister John 
Major's statement on "the policy of prevention in Kosovo." 
Rugova said that the incidents on the Yugoslav-Albanian border 
are "a provocation against Albania, but also against the ethnic 
Albanians in Kosovo." Rugova did not elaborate further on any 
of these issues, nor on his habitual claim about "the repression 
against the Albanians in Kosovo." 

</TEXT>

