<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Express Readiness To Join Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1401180394 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1400 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1401180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today three-hour talks were held by representatives 
of the Democratic Convention of Romania [CDR] and those of the 
Democratic Party-National Salvation Front [PD-FSN]. The goal of 
the talks, to which the press did not have access, was to find 
consensus elements in the views of the opposition parties that 
are prepared to assume responsibility for leading the country 
out of its current situation. 
  A statement released for the press after the conclusion of 
the talks says that in the opinion shared by the opposition 
parties, they are able to come up with concrete suggestions 
regarding both political and economic-social problems. Today's 
talks prove that the opposition parties have the necessary 
foresight, will, and competence to ensure the economic recovery, 
social peace, political stability, and international credibility 
of the country, the statement says. 
  Assessing that the current deadlock is the consequence of a 
government based on political alliances that are harmful for the 
country, as they allow for the access to power of certain 
non-democratic, anti-reform, extremist, and xenophobic forces, 
the current parliamentary opposition declares that it is ready 
to assume the responsibility for ruling the country. To that 
purpose the parliamentary majority has to be restructured and 
therefore the opposition expresses its readiness to set up a 
coalition government with the PDSR [Social Democracy Party of 
Romania -- ruling party]. 
  The responsibility now lies with those who hold the 
principal 
levers of the current political power. If the political 
proposal made by the opposition is ignored, the solution to this 
problem should be given by means of the direct vote of the 
nation [early elections], the statement concludes. 

</TEXT>

