<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Ethnic Unrest in Cluj Possible </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301084494 Bucharest EVENIMENTUL ZILEI in Romanian 4 Jan 
94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU1301084494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest EVENIMENTUL ZILEI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Bogdan Eduard: "Gheorghe Funar Will Change the </F>
Inscription on the Statue of the King of Hungary"] 
  [Text] Gheorghe Funar, mayor of the city of Cluj, chairman 
of PUNR [National Romanian Unity Party], has prepared a series 
of actions for this year intended to "please" the Hungarian 
ethnic minority. Thus, the mayor has decided to finalize work 
on the equestrian statue of King Matthias Corvinus in the center 
of the city by replacing the [Latin] inscription [on the 
pedestal] Mathias Rex with a new [Romanian] one, Matei Corvinul. 
  According to reliable sources, Funar regards the old 
inscription as a compromise solution arrived at by the 
communists and Horthysts [Hungarian fascists during World War 
II], and, therefore, it has to be eliminated right away so that 
it will not overshadow the great festivities to celebrate the 
anniversary of the 1859 Union [of Wallachia with Moldavia] that 
are to take place in Cluj on 24 January. 
  It should be noted that, on 6 December 1992, the measure 
[taken by Funar] to modify the equestrian statue of King 
Matthias [by adding a plaque belittling the personality of the 
king and hoisting the national colors all around the statute] 
triggered off unprecedented protests on behalf of the ethnic 
Hungarians living in the city. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

