<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Cited on NATO, Inflation, Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801094894 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0900 
GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak said that every 
country that accepts the American Partnership for Peace program 
would individually decide the scope of its cooperation with 
NATO. He added that the forms and scope of Poland's cooperation 
with NATO were also linked with the capacity of this year's 
budget. 
  In an interview for the Polish Radio Third Program, the 
prime 
minister said that details of Poland's cooperation with NATO, as 
part of the Partnership for Peace program, as well as the 
results of the recent visit by President Walesa and the prime 
minister to Prague, will be discussed at today's meeting of the 
government. 
  Waldemar Pawlak announced that this year, as an 
anti-inflation measure, the government would attempt to slow 
down the pace of official price rises [ceny urzedowe]. 
  The prime minister emphasized that the numerous changes, 
which have recently occurred in Poland, have been achieved in a 
democratic way, without the upheavals and conflicts which took 
place in other countries. 
  Waldemar Pawlak expressed the opinion that in the spring 
local government elections, it would be better to use the old 
electoral system instead of the new one proposed by the Social 
Democracy of the Polish Republic. According to the prime 
minister, councillors and representatives of the local 
government assemblies [sejmiki samorzadowe], with whom he 
recently had talks, were in favor of such a solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

