<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Introduces New, Convertible Dinar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601222894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2131 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1601222894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, 16 Jan (TANJUG) -- From 24 January 
Yugoslavs will have a new, convertible dinar, worth one German 
mark. According to the Decree on the New Dinar and the Decree 
on the Dinar Exchange Rate, adopted by the Federal Government 
this evening, the new dinar will be in circulation both in giro 
and in effective form [as received] and can be exchanged for any 
foreign currency. 
  At a news conference after the federal government's session, 
Dragoslav Avramovic, the head of the team of experts which made 
the economic policy programme, and Ratko Banovic, vice governor 
of the National Bank of Yugoslavia, explained to reporters that 
the old, existing dinar will continue to be used in financial 
transactions in the initial period. The rate between the old 
and the new dinar will be defined daily, on the basis of the 
exchange rate between the old dinar and foreign currencies. 
  A fund of $200 million from the National Bank of Yugoslavia 
has been prepared as a foreign exchange support for the first 
emission of the new dinar, scheduled to amount to $100 million. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

