<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Serbs Accused of `Bad Faith' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1801184594 Paris AFP in English 1829 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Geneva, Jan 18 (AFP) -- The Moslem-led Bosnian 
Government reacted angrily Tuesday to a UN refusal to back NATO 
air strikes against its opponents as new talks to end the 
21-month-old conflict ran into further roadblocks. With Bosnian 
Serbs retracting a previous offer to give the Moslems a third of 
the former Yugoslav republic in an ethnic carveup, peace 
mediators held out little hope for progress here. 
  "There is no particular reason for optimism," conference 
spokesman John Mills said after the European Community and 
United Nations mediators held separate talks with the warring 
Serbs, Croats and Moslems. 
  The talks coincided with further fighting in Bosnia and 
continuing hand-wringing in the West over its Yugoslavia policy. 
[passage omitted] 
  In the peace negotiations, which resumed here after being 
broken off on December 23 in Brussels, Moslems and Serbs accused 
each other of rejecting the EC peace plan for the ethnic 
division of their country. [passage omitted] 
  Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic called the Serb 
proposal unacceptable and [Bosnia-Herzegovina Ambassador to the 
UN] Sacirbey accused the Serbs of bad faith as they "have still 
not accepted the concept of a viable territory" for a future 
Moslem republic. [passage omitted] 
  Sacirbey said the Bosnian delegation had presented the 
Croats 
with new proposals concerning the Adriatic port of Neum, the 
southern city of Mostar and central Bosnia, but there were no 
details. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

