<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Milosevic, Silajdzic Comment </H4>
<F P=102> LD1801230394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2158 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801230394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, 18 Jan (TANJUG) -- The opening day of the 
Geneva negotiations ended this evening with extremely reserved 
assessments and forecasts by its participants, but with 
agreement that the dialogue be continued tomorrow. 
  Following the conclusion of bilateral negotiations with 
Muslim representatives, Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic 
stated that the degree of understanding is "to put it mildly, 
very, very modest." He added that he does not wish to judge it 
in advance, because they agreed to continue the negotiations 
tomorrow. 
  According to Milosevic, the Serb side has practically 
fulfilled European Union demands that the Muslims in Bosnia get 
33.3 percent of the territory, but, as he put it, the Muslim 
side has rejected this. 
  Milosevic said that the conditions exist for this bloody war 
to end, and this is the essence of everything. However, he 
noted that an endless dialogue is being conducted with the 
Muslim delegation, as it has continued to put forward fresh 
demands. "It is high time that peace was signed, after which 
bilateral or trilateral talks on coordinating contentious issues 
can continue," Milosevic said. 
  Referring to a Serbian-Croatian dialogue in the Palais des 
Nations this afternoon, Milosevic said that a high degree of 
understanding was achieved. He added that an identical approach 
to solving the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina exists. 
  Haris Silajdzic, prime minister in the pro-Muslim 
government, 
said that no progress was made in the talks with the Serbian 
side. He found it appropriate to express his regret that the 
"international community and the Western diplomacy do not 
support Bosnia, are maintaining the arms embargo and thus 
enabling an aggression and spread of fascism in Bosnia." 
  Silajdzic stressed that the Muslim side did not put forward 
fresh demands in this round of negotiations, apart from 
insisting on 33.5 percent of the territory and the return of 
"territories seized by force." 
  According to Silajdzic, the biggest concession made by the 
Muslim delegation was that it accepted three ethnic republics 
within a union, to the detriment of keeping an undivided Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

