<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Koljevic on `Decisive' 19 Jan Talks </H4>
<F P=102> LD1801232294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2225 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801232294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 18 Jan (TANJUG) -- Nikola Koljevic, vice 
president of the republic of Srpska, declared this evening that 
the Muslim delegation had come to the Geneva talks with demands 
that do not accord with the European Union [EU] proposal, and 
added that negotiations outside the framework of this proposal 
are not acceptable to the Serb side. 
  "The Muslims made certain new demands that are not in 
accordance with the existing EU proposal. Talks on this subject 
will resume tomorrow. However, the Serb side is adhering to the 
existing proposals and insists on them, so the talks depend on 
whether the Muslim side will accept the EU proposals or not," 
Koljevic said in an interview for TV Politika. 
  He added that "the Muslims demanded fresh territorial 
concessions beyond the framework of the EU proposal, that is, 
the Franco-German proposal which the Serbs had earlier agreed 
to." 
  "I believe that tomorrow's talks will be decisive. If the 
Muslim side rejects the EU proposals, the Serbs will present a 
new platform," Koljevic concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

