<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Granic Sees `Important Progress' </H4>
<F P=102> LD1801234294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2300 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801234294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking on the phone line from Geneva, where he is 
taking part in peace negotiations on Bosnia-Herzegovina, Mate 
Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and foreign minister, 
stated for the Croatian radio and television program "TV 
Parliament" this evening that Croatia will put forward a 
proposal to Serbia tomorrow which contains concrete conditions 
for normalizing relations and mutual recognition. It will also 
put forward a proposal to the Bosnian Muslim side on conditions 
for the urgent cessation of all hostilities and elements for 
drawing up internal boundaries. 
  As Minister Granic said, Croatia remains open to 
negotiations 
on the alliance between the two states, and hopes that progress 
will be reached in one of these fields. He also added that it 
is not realistic to expect a final agreement on 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to be reached at meetings which are to be 
continued tomorrow. 
  Speaking about the results of negotiations conducted today, 
the Croatian foreign minister stressed that what could be 
considered headway in talks with the Bosnian Muslim side was 
that they have finally put forward draft maps and that they have 
agreed to hold talks on the alliance between the Bosniak Muslim 
republic and the Croat Republic as well as talks on territorial 
settlement within the union of republics of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
We deem that this was important progress. 
  However, we are not happy with the proposals, but it is 
finally clear what they consider contentious and what their 
proposals to the Croatian side are, Mate Granic said in his 
phone call. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

