<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sarajevo Radio Reports </H4>
<F P=102> AU1901111794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0900 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1901111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, on the first day of Geneva peace talks, 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina delegation had many meetings, including 
one with Yasushi Akashi, special envoy of the UN secretary 
general and with the peace conference cochairmen Owen and 
Stoltenberg. On that occasion, our state delegation presented 
the stands established by the Assembly of the Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The three-hour talks last night between the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina delegation and the delegation of the Serbian 
aggressor, which was headed by Slobodan Milosevic, ended without 
any major results. It was agreed for these talks to resume 
today at 1100. 
  During the talks with the delegation of the Serbian 
aggressor, Alija Izetbegovic, president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, made remarks about the map that 
was already discussed in the past. All attempts by our official 
to reach a solution for the eastern and western Bosnia, however, 
have hit a barrier of silence in Milosevic's camp. The only 
news during yesterday's meeting was Milosevic's statement that 
the Serbian aggressor's side agreed to Sarajevo's remaining 
under two-year UN administration. 
  The basic problem in last night's talks was in the fact that 
the Serb aggressor's side refuses to meet our delegation's 
demand to give back the territories occupied by force on which 
Muslim Bosniaks constituted majority population before the 
aggression on Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

