<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Representative Offices To Open 15 Feb </H4>
<F P=102> LD1901143294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1338 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Quotation marks as received] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, 19 Jan (TANJUG) -- The Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia and the Republic of Croatia signed a joint 
declaration in Geneva today on the process for the normalization 
of mutual relations and the opening of representative offices of 
their governments in Belgrade and Zagreb. The offices will open 
and begin work on 15 February 1994. 
  A joint statement signed by the two foreign ministers, 
Vladislav Jovanovic and Mate Granic, reads: 
  "The Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the Republic of 
Croatia, starting from the positive experiences in their joint 
efforts to speed up the peace process to resolve the crisis in 
the area of the former Yugoslavia, and guided by the provisions 
of the UN Charter and the basic documents of the CSCE, and 
aspiring to the establishment of good-neighborly relations, and 
in their desire to contribute in a decisive way to finding a 
just and lasting solution to the crisis in the area of the 
former Yugoslavia -- and to the reestablishment of stability in 
this part of Europe -- agree to embark upon the process of the 
normalization of mutual relations. 
  As a first step in this direction it has been decided to 
open 
in Belgrade and Zagreb official representative offices of the 
two governments -- a Federal Republic of Yugoslavia office in 
Zagreb and an office of the Republic of Croatia in Belgrade. 
  The opening of these offices should ease interstate 
relations 
and contacts, and contribute to the development of mutual trust, 
including the process of the normalization of Serbo-Croat 
relations, in the interest of peace, cooperation and stability 
in the region. 
  The Governments of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and 
the 
Republic of Croatia will ensure the technical and other 
conditions enabling the offices to work efficiently, work which 
will begin on 15 February 1994." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49858 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu012aa_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-012 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations in Geneva Discuss Bosnia Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   FRY Foreign Minister Comments </H4>
<F P=102> AU1901151294 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1901151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Dragan Colovic from Geneva] </F>
  [Text] At exactly 1410 a joint statement was signed here 
in Geneva on the beginning of the process of normalization of 
relations between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia [FRY] and 
Croatia. This important document was signed by Vladislav 
Jovanovic and Mate Granic, foreign ministers of the FRY and 
Croatia, respectively. The signing ceremony was attended by 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, Montenegrin President 
Momir Bulatovic, Radovan Karadzic, president of the republic of 
Srpska, and Croatian President Franjo Tudjman. 
  It has been decided that as the first step toward the 
normalization of relations between the FRY and Croatia the two 
governments open representative offices in Zagreb and Belgrade. 
The joint communique states that the opening of the 
aforementioned representative offices will improve relations and 
facilitate contacts between the two states, as well as 
contribute toward mutual trust and the process of normalization 
of Serbian-Croatian relations in the interest of peace, 
cooperation, and stability in the region. The representative 
offices of the FRY in Zagreb and of Croatia in Belgrade will 
commence work on 15 February. 
  It appears that the signing of the aforementioned statement, 
which implies the beginning of the normalization in relations 
between the FRY and Croatia, is so far the only tangible result 
of the very difficult two-day negotiations in Geneva. The 
negotiations will continue this afternoon. 
  Here is what Federal Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic 
stated after the signing of the joint declaration, especially 
for Belgrade Radio: 
  [Begin recording] [Jovanovic] The document that has just 
been signed is an important event and document because it 
sanctions the positive efforts made by the FRY and the Republic 
of Croatia in the current peace process in a positive way, 
especially with regard to the settlement of the Bosnian crisis. 
This document also stresses their determination to establish 
closer bilateral contacts, to establish direct communication 
links in the form of offices, and we are convinced that this 
will help the (?establishment) of peace and the prospects for 
the political settling of all outstanding issues in relations 
between the two countries and the broader region of Yugoslavia. 
  We hope that this statement will have positive effects on 
the 
(?situation) and the settlement of the crisis in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, because (?it represents) a sign of political 
goodwill and unity in the efforts of political factors to 
politically overcome the problems that require exclusively 
political solutions and not solutions with force. 
  [Colovic] Mr. Jovanovic, how do you assess the two-day talks 
in Geneva? 
  [Jovanovic] They are very complex, very slow, and contain 
many anachronisms, especially by the Muslim delegation, which 
has obviously come here with the intention not to sign peace but 
to make it more complicated, that is, to make its realization 
more difficult. This is the most negative moment in the work so 
far. On the contrary, however, there are continuous efforts, 
efforts made by the cochairmen and the Serbian and the Croatian 
sides. Thanks to this, one could say that there are still some 
chances of saving the peace process this afternoon and evening, 
and if we can be optimists without having much reason to be, to 
bring this process closer to an end. 
  [Colovic] Thank you Mr. Jovanovic. 
  [Jovanovic] Thank you. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

