<H3> <TI>   Sarajevo Accuses UNHCR of `Underworld' Tactics </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801201594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1801201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] The members of the [Sarajevo] 
City Council have assessed the latest round of humanitarian aid 
as one of the worst so far. That is why a meeting was organized 
yesterday with Tony Land, chief of the UNHCR office in Sarajevo. 
Mayor Muhamed Kresevljakovic asked Mr. Land whether the obvious 
reduction in the humanitarian aid represented yet another form 
of pressure on the Bosnia-Herzegovina authorities, and whether 
the UNHCR had merged with the European underworld, which 
normally resorted to such tactics. 
  Tony Land vehemently rejected this, justifying the 
increasingly poor deliveries to the Saralians by the wintry 
conditions, which limit the number of flights, by the frequent 
firing at UNHCR aircraft, and the lack of land corridors. The 
representatives of the city authorities proposed to Land that on 
one day no flour should be brought into the city, but instead 
all the flights should be used to bring proteins and sugar into 
Sarajevo. Land said that he had no say in the kind of goods 
that were delivered by air. 
  All in all, the meeting with the chief of the Sarajevo UNHCR 
office was assessed as unsatisfactory. That is why the members 
of the Sarajevo City Council have sent another letter from 
today's session to UNHCR's Sadako Ogata, in which they inform 
her about the very difficult humanitarian situation in Sarajevo, 
asking her to do something improve it. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

