<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Convoys Encounter Civilian Blockades </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801163394 Paris AFP in English 1544 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Sarajevo, Jan 18 (AFP) -- The humanitarian 
situation is "alarming" in central Bosnia and "desperate" in the 
besieged Moslem-held town of Maglaj, in the north, a UN official 
said here Tuesday [18 January]. For the third day running 
Tuesday aid convoys headed from the Adriatic to central Bosnia 
had to be called off because roads were blocked by demonstrating 
civilians in Moslem-held areas, UN High Commissioner for 
Refugees (UNHCR) spokesman Kris Janowski said here. 
  On Monday, some 300 people held up a food convoy between 
Zenica and Kakanj, central Bosnia, and police had to fire into 
the air to disperse them, he said. Last week, three UNHCR 
convoys were attacked in Moslem-held areas, notably between 
Gornji Vakuf and Novi Travnik, and a British armoured vehicle 
had to fire into the air to disperse civilians, the spokesman 
also said. UNHCR representatives suggested civilians were angry 
at the way food was distributed by the Bosnian authorities. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

