<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communists: Partnership Leads To `Rivalry' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801201994 Prague RUDE PRAVO in Czech 15 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801201994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague RUDE PRAVO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["(kou)"-signed report: "The Communist Party of Bohemia and </F>
Moravia: Partnership for Peace Will Lead To Rivalry"] 
  [Text] Prague -- Partnership for Peace will not contribute 
to cooperation, but, on the contrary, to rivalry. This 
statement was made by Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia 
[KSCM] Chairman M. Grebenicek at a news conference. He 
expressed his dissatisfaction with the Czech Government's 
immediate agreement to this proposal without a public debate and 
called for a referendum. According to Deputy Chairman M. 
Ransdorf, the Partnership will make considerable claims on the 
Czech Republic's budget. He emphasized the likelihood of a 
"certain yielding of part of our state sovereignty" without 
clear security guarantees. According to the KSCM, collective 
security should be based on the CSCE. 
  M. Stiborova, chairwoman of the Left Bloc Party, said that 
Partnership for Peace will not resolve our entry into NATO. In 
her opinion, not even the expansion of NATO is a path toward 
collective European security. According to Stiborova, the CSCE 
should form the basis for European security. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

