<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister on Budget Surplus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801135094 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1100 
GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] The 1993 state budget has recorded a 
surplus exceeding one billion crowns. Marie Ruzickova is in the 
studio with the details. 
  [Ruzickova] The finance minister [Ivan Kocarnik] said that 
total revenue, which amounted to 358 billion crowns, meant that 
the budget's revenue of has been fulfilled by 100.8 percent. 
Expenditure, amounting to almost 357 billion crowns, was 
fulfilled by 100.5 percent. 
  The Czech Republic is the only country, of those that are 
undergoing the process of transformation, that recorded a budget 
surplus. Minister Kocarnik thinks this result is a success. 
  [Begin Kocarnik recording] I regard this result as a 
success, 
as a further successful step of transformation in the Czech 
Republic, which has brought a positive contribution to the 
overall stabilization of prices, countered inflation, and 
contributed to achieving the basic objectives we set out for 
ourselves for the year 1993 [end recording]. 
  [Ruzickova] The budget surplus could have been higher by 
another 4.6 billion crowns. This sum is the credit we gave to 
Slovakia in clearing transactions. According to Minister 
Kocarnik, both sides are considering changes in the 
[Czech-Slovak] Payments Agreement. These changes would mean a 
gradual abolition of the so called "old bloc" [stary blok] and a 
possible widening of the exchange rate margin from 5 to 10 
percent. No increase of marginal credit [mezni uver] is 
envisaged for the time being. 
  On talks of the Czech-Slovak property commission, Ivan 
Kocarnik said that this commission should meet in a foreseeable 
future and outline the final solution to outstanding problems. 

</TEXT>

