<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Personnel Reduction To End in 1995 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801202094 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 15 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["(jem)"-signed report: "The Reduction in Army Personnel </F>
Will Probably Be Halted Next Year"] 
  [Text] Prague -- The reduction in army personnel will be 
halted in 1995 at 65,000 men. This corresponds to the treaty on 
reducing conventional armed forces in Europe. A more 
substantial reduction had originally been envisaged. The army's 
significance, however, will increase appreciably, among other 
things, because of the continuing conflicts in the former 
Yugoslavia and in the southern regions of the former Soviet 
Union, said Oldrich Holecek of the Defense Ministry's Press 
Department. At the moment, the planned number of Czech Army 
personnel is 92,599. The actual number is somewhat lower. 
Roughly a third of the army is made up of career soldiers. In 
two years, however, professionals should make up 50 percent of 
the army, while soldiers on their basic service should make up 
the other 50 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

