<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Council of Europe Conclude Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801180694 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1500 
GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801180694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Council of Europe experts today ended two-day talks 
with representatives of the Slovak Government on a 
government-sponsored bill on the territorial administrative 
division of Slovakia. Renata Havranova, editor of PRACE daily, 
reports from Bratislava: 
  [Havranova] (Mario Martins), head of the delegation of 
Council of Europe experts, noted that since his first visit last 
April, considerable progress on the part of the Slovak bodies 
has been noted in tackling territorial administrative division. 
Council of Europe experts are of the opinion that the proposed 
integration of state administration on a horizontal level could 
improve not only its efficiency, but also the coordination of 
branch activities and, above all, relations among citizens. 
Slovakia should speed up the process of decentralization so 
that appropriate laws can be put into practice prior to local 
elections. Experts consider as too liberal the principle of 
voluntarism in the cooperation of self-administration bodies 
when setting up offices. The Slovak Republic should safeguard 
the standard level of state administration by laws. 
  The experts pointed out that the problem of national 
minorities cannnot be solved by artificial division of the state 
into regions. They consider the geographical spread of 
minorities as one of the many factors of the reform. 
Representatives of the Council of Europe recommended permanent 
dialogue, above all, with the Hungarian minority. The problems 
of this minority, in their view, could become a question of 
human rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

