<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Nordic Battalion Departs With Tanks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801150694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1257 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, 18 Jan (TANJUG) -- Blue Helmet members 
of the Nordic Battalion, who have stayed in Pancevo's Stevica 
Jovanovic barracks for several months, departed this morning 
together with 11 Leopard tanks from the territory of the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia, TANJUG has learned from the Federal 
Government Committee for Cooperation with the UN Peace Force. 
  The members of UNPROFOR [UN Peacekeeping Forces] from 
Sweden, 
Denmark and Norway were deployed in the Tuzla area. One part of 
this unit spent several months in the Pancevo barracks, waiting 
for permission from the authorities of the republic of Srpska to 
transport the 11 peace force tanks to Tuzla. 
  The republic of Srpska, however, regarded this intention as 
an attempt at irregularly applying the existing Blue Helmets 
mandate. 
  Representatives of the republic of Srpska army pointed out 
that UNPROFOR was tasked with keeping peace and providing 
humanitarian aid to civilian population, in the course of which 
they were authorized to carry personal and defensive weapons. A 
tank of the Leopard kind is neither a personal nor a defensive 
weapon. 
  Since no agreement on the passage of the tanks was reached, 
the Nordic soldiers have left Pancevo. In addition to the tanks 
and soldiers, 23 armored personnel carriers have also left 
Stevica Jovanovic barracks aboard three trains, the federal 
government committee says. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

