<H3> <TI>   UN, UNHCR Officials Oppose Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1801143994 Paris AFP in English 1419 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1801143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Geneva, Jan 18 (AFP) -- A senior UN 
representative has recommended against using allied warplanes in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina as proposed by NATO to relieve trapped UN 
soldiers and reopen a key airport, officials said here Tuesday 
[18 January]. UN officials confirmed the Bosnian Serbs had 
already agreed to the replacement of some 180 Canadian troops 
stranded for six months in the eastern enclave of Srebrenica, 
making military action unnecessary. The assessments were 
contained in a report handed Monday to UN secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali by Yasushi Akashi, his special 
representative for the former Yugoslavia, the officials said. 
[passage omitted] 
  Marrak Goulding, deputy UN secretary general for political 
affairs, was dispatched to Brussels on Tuesday to brief Manfred 
Woerner, secretary general of the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation, on the UN plans. UN High Commissioner for 
Refugees Sadako Ogata welcomed Akashi's call to avoid air 
strikes on the Serbs. "It was not a solution," she told AFP. "It 
would have been an all-out war and what do we do after that?" 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

