<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Klaus, Boross Meet, Comment </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201152894 Prague CTK in English 1336 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- The Czechs and the 
Hungarians hold similar views on the NATO Partnership For Peace 
project, Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus and Hungarian Premier Peter 
Boross said after their meeting today. 
  Partnership For Peace is the only possible realistic project 
and both countries want to play an active part in the 
initiative, Klaus said. Both countries see the project as a 
means of attaining full NATO membership, Boross said. 
  Hungary sees somewhat greater potential for the overlapping 
of common interests, in the Visegrad countries (Poland, Hungary, 
the Czech Republic and Slovakia) cooperation than the Czech 
Republic, Klaus said, adding however that he agreed with Boross 
on the extension of concrete and practical cooperation and above 
all on the opening of a Central European Free Trade Zone. 
  Hungary, too, is not interested in building institutions 
reminiscent of the former COMECON [Council for Mutural Economic 
Assistance], but in concrete cooperation, Boross said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

