<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kovac To Seek NATO Membership </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201162994 Prague CTK in English 1409 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- Slovakia will use the U.S. 
Partnership for Peace project to seek full membership of NATO, 
Slovak President Michal Kovac said in a meeting today with Czech 
President Vaclav Havel. 
  Czech Presidential office head Lubos Dobrovsky told 
journalists that Kovac described the partnership initiative as a 
"great opportunity for central European countries' integration 
into Euro-American civilization and the sphere of European 
values, which are protected and guaranteed by NATO as a 
militarily-formed security structure." 
  Havel's talks with Kovac were one of a series of talks with 
heads of state of other Visegrad Group countries (Poland and 
Hungary) held at Prague castle today. 
  After the talks with Havel, Kovac left for talks with U.S. 
President Bill Clinton. After their negotiations there will be 
a working dinner given by Clinton for his Visegrad partners at 
the U.S. Ambassador's residence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

