<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Walesa Airs Doubts to Clinton </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201183494 Warsaw PAP in English 1716 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan. 12 -- Poland will not block the 
U.S.-proposed "Partnership for Peace" initiative, President Lech 
Walesa said in Prague on Wednesday during the talks between 
Polish and United States delegations presided over by both 
countries' presidents and attended by their prime ministers. 
  Director of the Press and Information Department in the 
Foreign Ministry Wladyslaw Klaczynski told newsmen after the 
meeting that U.S. President Bill Clinton described the 
initiative as opening doors, not setting up barriers. 
  President Lech Walesa stressed Poland's doubts concerning 
the 
initiative in the light of both Polish past experience and the 
present situation. President Walesa pointed out Poland's 
determination to effectively and quickly integrate with the 
European structures which is not intended to work against the 
interests of Russia. 
  Bill Clinton reiterated that U.S. security is connected with 
the security of the central and eastern Europe and said that the 
"Partnership for Peace" is a project valuable as such and is not 
a compromise between doing nothing and full NATO membership. 
  Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak, who was referring mainly to 
economic issues, stressed the need to start a "partnership for 
development." Bill Clinton replied that he had encouraged 
businessmen present at the recent E.C. summit in Brussels to 
expand their investments in eastern and central Europe and 
appealed to western leaders to facilitate the access of eastern 
European goods to western markets. 
  President Lech Walesa especially emphasized the necessity 
for 
western Europe's greater effort in the integration processes. 

</TEXT>

