<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Havel, Goncz Discuss Bilateral Issues </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201205794 Prague CTK in English 1817 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- At a meeting with Czech 
President Vaclav Havel today, Hungarian President Arpad Goncz 
said that Hungary sees the Partnership for Peace as a signal 
that NATO is reckoning with the countries of the Visegrad Group 
(Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, and Poland) but that their 
membership would not be automatic, Havel's spokesman Ladislav 
Spacek told CTK. 
  Spacek said that according to Goncz, Hungary does not see 
the 
Partnership for Peace as a substitute for membership, but rather 
as an open opportunity for everyone. He also admitted the 
possibility of individual admission into NATO for Central and 
Eastern European countries. The two presidents agreed, Spacek 
said, that it is necessary to emphasize the stability of the 
region, which they consider a condition for carrying out the 
Partnership for Peace. 
  Havel and Goncz assured each other that in the near future, 
experts from both countries would set up contacts with NATO 
military representatives on preparing the initiative. On the 
topic of bilateral relations, the two presidents agreed that 
they are interested in deepening economic and other cooperation. 
Czech and Hungarian Foreign Ministers Josef Zieleniec and Geza 
Jeszenszky also participated in the talks. 

</TEXT>

