<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meciar, Kovac Meet With Press </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201205694 Prague CTK in English 1907 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- Issues concerning ethnic 
minorities are guided by pan-European norms which Slovakia 
respects but holds a different opinion of the priority of civic 
and ethnic rights, Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar told 
journalists after his talks with a Hungarian delegation tonight. 
He said that unlike Hungary, Slovakia considered the 
implementation of the ethnic principle in building states to be 
overcome. 
  Meciar said that ethnic conflicts benefited nobody and 
expressed the conviction that Slovaks and Hungarians would 
succeed in coping with the problem of ethnic minorities. He was 
reacting to a question about the role played by the problem of 
the Hungarian ethnic minority in Slovakia in the integration 
processes within the Visegrad Group. 
  Meciar said each of the Visegrad Four countries (the Czech 
Republic, Hungary, Poland, and Slovakia) was partly responsible 
for the group's stagnation. He stressed that the possible 
withdrawal of the Czech Republic from the group would probably 
result in its disintegration, not in its transformation into a 
"Visegrad Troika." He added that Slovakia would continue to 
seek cooperation and coordination of its policies with the 
Czechs. 
  In reference to the fact that Slovakia was often omitted 
from 
talks about possible admission of new members into NATO, Slovak 
President Michal Kovac said that U.S. President Bill Clinton had 
assured him that the United States had never excluded Slovakia 
and was not going to do so. This problem was in fact solved 
today when all the Visegrad countries accepted the Partnership 
for Peace project, which gives equal chances to all of them, 
Kovac said. 
  He said it was not surprising that no joint statement was 
adopted at the conclusion of the Visegrad leaders' meeting with 
Clinton, because its main goal was to inform Clinton about the 
Visegrad countries' stands on Partnership for Peace. 
  Kovac said that Clinton had accepted his invitation to 
attend 
the celebrations of the 50th anniversary of the Slovak National 
Uprising in summer, though he may send somebody else to 
represent him if he does not come himself. The anti-Nazi 
uprising broke out in Slovakia on August 29, 1944. 
  The economic issues, too, were discussed by the Slovak 
delegation, headed by President Michal Kovac, during the talks 
with U.S. President Bill Clinton, Kovac told journalists today. 
Slovak leaders appealed to Clinton to bear Slovakia in mind 
when investment is considered, which Clinton promised, Kovac 
said. 
  Several countries are striving to become an intermediary in 
trade between Europe, the United States, and Russia, noted 
Premier Vladimir Meciar. The Western economics will follow the 
easiest and most suitable way, he added. 
  Meciar said that some questions of economic relations with 
the Czech Republic were still to be settled. The most delicate 
one is reclaiming joint foreign debts, where the two countries 
should establish a precise strategy, he said. 
  Meciar mentioned the Slovak gold allegedly withheld by the 
Czech National Bank accumulated by the pro-Nazi Slovak state 
during World War Two, and the deficit of the Czechoslovak State 
Bank as the unresolved issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

