<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hungarians Hold News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201195694 Budapest MTI in English 1918 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, 12 January (MTI) -- Central Europe must not 
become a security vacuum, President Arpad Goncz said at a news 
conference after the U.S.-Visegrad consultation in Prague on 
Wednesday [12 January]. 
  Goncz said that the four Visegrad countries -- the Czech 
Republic, Hungary, Poland, and Slovakia -- are in agreement over 
all relevant issues, with only minor geographical differences. 
Goncz believed the plan will be tested by concrete cooperation. 
Prosperity is also important -- Budapest approaches security in 
a broader context than the military alone. 
  Prime Minister Peter Boross stressed the peace-partnership 
scheme as the first far-reaching international initiative by an 
American President in office for several years to come. 
  Boross was happy with his talks with his Czech, Polish, and 
Slovak counterparts, and called for greater efforts to solve 
problems delaying setting up the Visegrad free-trade zone. 

</TEXT>

