<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on News Conference </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201205594 Prague CTK in English 1948 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- Today is a historical day 
of extraordinary importance for further political, security, and 
economic developments in Europe, Hungarian President Arpad Goncz 
told journalists today. 
  He underlined the importance of the Partnership for Peace 
plan as an important element for a stable Central and Eastern 
Europe. It is necessary for Ukraine and Russia to develop 
democratically and to foster good relations both with the United 
States and NATO, Goncz stated. Goncz said that the Visegrad 
Four countries had expressed the same views on important issues 
related to the Partnership for Peace. 
  Hungarian Premier Peter Boross stressed the economic aspects 
of the project and mentioned the planned conference in the 
United States which was to enhance Western investment in Central 
and Eastern Europe. He emphasized the importance of concrete 
steps in military cooperation. 
  Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky said that the 
question of the military exercises in Hungary would be specified 
after NATO General Staff sends its experts to the Visegrad Four 
countries. He added that joint military maneuvers in Hungary 
were first to be approved by parliament. 
  Jeszenszky said that an agreement with Slovakia was not 
possible until the problems of ethnic Hungarians in Slovakia 
were resolved. He stressed that a large number of equally 
important problems of Slovak-Hungarian relations were still 
pending. 

</TEXT>

