<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Parties on `Danger' of `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101214694 Prague CTK in English 2047 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 11 (CTK) -- The American Partnership 
for Peace project is assessed by the coalition parties, the 
Czech Social Democratic Party (CSSD), and the Liberal National 
Social Party (LSNS) as a first step towards the desirable 
cooperation of the Czech Republic with NATO, a poll conducted by 
CTK today revealed. 
  The government coalition consists of the Civic Democratic 
Party (ODS), Civic Democratic Alliance (ODA), Christian 
Democratic Party (KDS), and Christian Democratic 
Union-Czechoslovak People's Party (KDU-CSL). 
  This view is not shared by two opposition parties, the KSCM 
(Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia) and the Left Bloc (LB) 
as they consider it danger for the Czech Republic's sovereignty. 
  Vera Zezulkova, a spokesman for the KSCM, expressed fear 
that 
the project, as a first step to NATO membership, will make it 
possible to "engage the Czech Republic in possible future 
conflicts serving the interest of the powers." She notes that 
the scheme envisages joint maneuvers as well as stay of foreign 
troops in the Czech Republic. "This, of course, does not 
correspond at all to the interests of most Czech people, either 
with respect to our security or to expenses." 
  A pan-European system of collective security, not NATO, is 
necessary for "new European Security," Jaroslav Ortman, a deputy 
for the LB told CTK. 

</TEXT>

