<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Havel Meets With Walesa </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201195494 Prague CTK in English 1032 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- The hope that good joint 
use will be made of the meetings on European security being held 
in Prague was expressed by Polish President Lech Walesa during 
talks with Czech President Vaclav Havel today. 
  Havel received Walesa in the Brozik Room of Prague Castle, 
thus opening a series of bilateral talks at the highest level 
between the leaders of the Visegrad countries (the Czech 
Republic, Poland, Slovakia, and Hungary). At the same time a 
series of bilateral meetings is taking place between U.S. 
President Bill Clinton and the presidents of Hungary, Poland, 
and Slovakia (Clinton talked to Havel yesterday.) 
  After meeting Havel, Walesa told journalists that he wanted 
to consider, together with the other presidents of Central 
European countries, how best they could serve their nations. 
  Poland is one of the most enthusiastic advocates of the 
fastest possible integration of Central European countries into 
NATO. In recent days the Polish press has also expressed 
dissatisfaction with the way in which the Czechs organized the 
Prague meetings. 
  President Walesa also told the independent Czech daily 
LIDOVE 
NOVINY that he was disappointed at the Czech Government's having 
scheduled Clinton to meet each of the Visegrad heads separately 
instead of there being a joint Visegrad meeting. The Czech side 
had also insisted that a joint statement would not be made by 
the Visegrad Four, he said. If the talks were not successful, 
Walesa said, Poland would be "forced to say that it was the 
fault of the organizers." 
  President Havel has made no statement on today's meeting 
with 
Walesa. 

</TEXT>

