<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hungarian Spokesman Cited </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201171694 Budapest MTI in English 1115 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201171694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 12 (MTI) -- The Prague talks between U.S. 
President Bill Clinton and Hungarian leaders -- President Arpad 
Goncz, Prime Minister Peter Boross and Foreign Minister Geza 
Jeszenszky -- focussed on the security policy situation of 
Central Europe, Hungarian Foreign Affairs Spokesman Janos Herman 
said. 
  In the hour-long meeting, President Clinton confirmed that 
the United States is paying great attention to the region. 
Security in Central Europe, he said, is important for both 
Washington and NATO. 
  The Hungarian delegation welcomed the Partnership for Peace 
plan and reaffirmed their country's preparedness to take an 
active part in it. 
  President Clinton said that security is not simply a 
military 
issue, but also a political and an economic one. The United 
States considers it important to promote economic development in 
Hungary and the region, the president added. 
  The leaders discussed the Yugoslav crisis as well. The 
Hungarian foreign affairs spokesman stated: "I consider it 
important that the Hungarian delegation was able to directly 
inform the U.S. administration on how a neighbouring country 
sees the efforts made so far to settle the crisis in Yugoslavia, 
and what it considers to be desirable steps." 
  The spokesman said President Clinton expressed his 
appreciation of the stability of Hungarian democracy. 
Washington considered the new prime minister's smooth and rapid 
election as a sign of this stability, Herman said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

