<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton, Visegrad Leaders Continue Prague Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Klaus Cited on Relations With Poland </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201163894 Prague CTK in English 1214 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- Relations between the Czech 
Republic and Poland are not as tense as it might seem from some 
newspapers' headlines, Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus said today 
after talks with his Polish counterpart Waldemar Pawlak. After 
the talks both premiers expressed their countries' willingness 
to cooperate, particularly in concrete economic projects. 
  Pawlak said that, in addition to the Partnership For Peace 
Initiative, partnership for economic development was significant 
at present. He said that frequent contacts between the two 
countries' premiers should be followed up by meetings between 
the two countries' ministers and businessmen. 
  Together with Polish President Lech Walesa and Foreign 
Minister Andrzej Olechowski, Pawlak is in Prague attending talks 
between leaders of the Visegrad Group countries (the Czech 
Republic, Slovakia, Poland and Hungary) and a U.S. delegation 
led by President Bill Clinton. 

</TEXT>

