<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Bosnia Peace Talks in Geneva </TI></H3>
<H4>   Belgrade-Zagreb Accord Highlighted </H4>
<F P=102> LD2001150694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1339 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By diplomatic editor Stevan Cordas; "pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 20 (TANJUG) -- The agreements reached 
between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.) and Croatia 
and between the Bosnian Serbs and Bosnian Croats to begin 
normalizing the mutual relations have salvaged the Geneva peace 
process and made its resumption on February 10 possible, despite 
the fact that the Bosnian Muslims have done everything to 
undermine it, according to diplomatic circles in Belgrade. 
  Diplomatic circles in Belgrade set out on Thursday that the 
agreements signed between the F.R.Y. and Croatia and between the 
Serb Republic (RS) and Herceg-Bosna in Geneva on Wednesday will 
also facilitate the resolution of the conflict in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  According to the same circles, it is extremely important 
that 
the agreements signed in Geneva proceed from the de facto 
situation which is practically becoming a de jure one. The RS 
and Herceg-Bosna, the states of the Bosnian Serbs and Bosnian 
Croats, respectively, have signed the document on the 
normalization of relations although they have not 
internationally been recognized as sovereign states. At the 
same time, Croatia has signed a similar document with the F.R.Y. 
which is recognized as a state, although its right to continuity 
in relation to the former Socialist Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia is disputed. 
  It is believed in Belgrade that, by signing the document on 
the normalization of relations with the F.R.Y., Croatia has 
abandoned the option of war as a means of resolving its 
relations with the Republic of Serb Krajina (RSK). 
  It is set out in Belgrade in that context that what is 
involved is only the beginning of a normalization process, which 
absolutely in no way delves into relations between Zagreb and 
the RSK and in no way prejudices the eventual solution. It is 
said that the mutual recognition between Belgrade and Zagreb and 
the establishment of diplomatic relations between them has most 
likely been left for the final stage of the process. 
  As far as the Bosnian Muslims are concerned, it is obvious 
that they have in a way been isolated in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
since Wednesday, since their hitherto strategy of insisting on 
the war option has totally been defeated. 
  It is beyond doubt that the Bosnian Muslims will no longer 
be 
able to use Serbs as an alleged excuse when they sit down at the 
negotiating table in Geneva again on February 10. RS President 
Radovan Karadzic was right when he said on the eve of the latest 
round of the Geneva talks that "nothing will any longer be the 
same" in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

