<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Bosnia Peace Talks in Geneva </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ministers on FRY-Croatia Accord </H4>
<F P=102> LD2001165394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1554 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Podgorica, 20 Jan (TANJUG)--In connection with the 
signing of the joint statement on the normalization of relations 
between the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and Croatia in Geneva 
yesterday, Vladislav Jovanovic, federal minister for foreign 
affairs, said that the two sides agreed to resolve all problems 
by political means. "I hope that this means renouncing violent 
means, especially war, as a means of resolving disputed issues," 
Jovanovic said in today's interview with Montenegrin Radio. 
  The opening of an office in Belgrade and Zagreb means 
precisely that--not more and not less. This is not the 
establishing of diplomatic relations or the recognition of 
Croatia, Jovanovic stressed. 
  The problem of the Republic of Serb Krajina should be dealt 
with in line with the Vance-Owen plan, through direct talks with 
representatives of the Croatian Government. The Geneva 
agreement does not prejudice the solution for Krajina, the 
foreign minister said. 
  The minister of foreign affairs of the Republic of Serb 
Krajina [RSK], Slobodan Jarcevic said during the same program 
that the RSK views the agreement between Jovanovic and [Croatian 
Foreign Minister Mate] Granic only as the normalization of 
relations between two countries, which he does not oppose. 
  "The RSK adheres to its stance that is must preserve its 
state, and that it must participate as an equal partner in all 
agreements on the territory of the former Yugoslavia. If 
Croatia signed the agreement hoping to return the RSK into its 
state framework, it is wrong," Jarcevic stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

