<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Agreement Signed With Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Jarcevic Assesses Agreement </H4>
<F P=102> LD1901145994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1354 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 19 Jan (TANJUG) -- Slobodan Jarcevic, 
minister for foreign affairs of the republic of Serb Krajina, 
said today that the joint statement signed today in Geneva by 
the ministers for foreign affairs of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia and the Republic of Croatia "does not infringe on the 
integrity and sovereignty of the republic of Serb Krajina." 
  A public statement signed by Jarcevic says that this joint 
statement, signed by Vladislav Jovanovic and Mate Granic, 
envisages mutual recognition, normalization of relations and the 
introduction of representative offices in Belgrade and Zagreb. 
"The Republic of Croatia can sign international treaties and 
make agreements only for the territories under its control and 
those that are not disputable," the statement says. Invoking 
CSCE documents, as stated, cannot imply the borders desired by 
the government of the Republic of Croatia, but the real ones. 
  Jarcevic stresses that the joint statement by Yugoslavia and 
Croatia in its reference to the UN Charter "relates to those 
provisions that regulate peaceful solutions to disputes and a 
people's right to self-determination," something "that implies 
the will of the people of the republic of Serb Krajina 
articulated clearly at their referendum, the statement 
emphasizes." 
  The government of the republic of Serb Krajina, as stated, 
welcomes the peace process in the area of the former Yugoslavia 
and the normalization of relations between the Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia and the Republic of Croatia, and believes that 
"this will contribute to the restoration of peace along the 
borders between the republic of Serb Krajina and the Republic of 
Croatia. 

</TEXT>

