<H3> <TI>   Peace Agreement Signed With Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<H4>   HSLS Condemns Accord </H4>
<F P=102> LD2001172494 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2001172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, some Croatian opposition parties commented on 
the declaration signed in Geneva yesterday. In its public 
statement on the joint declaration by the Republic of Croatia 
and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, the Croatian Social 
Liberal Party [HSLS] stresses that there is no justification for 
a policy which seeks an ally in an aggressor and an enemy in a 
second victim of aggression. The HSLS maintains that the 
priority task of Croatia's policy should be an agreement with 
the political leadership of Bosnia-Herzegovina's Muslims whereas 
the joint statement by Croatia and the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia will render such an agreement more difficult. 
  The HSLS believes that relations with the Federal Republic 
of 
Yugoslavia can be normalized once it has recognized the Croatian 
state within its internationally recognized borders, the HSLS 
says in its statement. The statement was signed by its 
chairman, Drazen Budisa. 

</TEXT>

