<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic on Relations With Hungary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901223794 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
2100 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Szilveszter Varga from Belgrade] </F>
  [Text] Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky will be 
received by his Yugoslav counterpart, Vladislav Jovanovic, who 
said in an interview with MTI that they had been able to 
preserve minimal mutual trust between Yugoslavia and Hungary. 
Jovanovic stressed that Hungary had shown a flexible attitude 
in connection with the application of the sanctions, in spite of 
the fact that Hungarian representatives at international forums 
were still objecting to Yugoslavia's participation in the work 
of these bodies. 
  Belgrade would like Hungary to change this position. 
Jovanovic especially held as a grievance the fact that a few 
weeks ago the Hungarian representative to the UN General 
Assembly voted in favor of lifting the Bosnian arms embargo. 
  Talking about the intimidation of the [ethnic] Hungarians in 
Vojvodina, the Yugoslav foreign minister said that this was 
suggested to them from beyond the border. Jovanovic added: 
Fears that are voiced in Hungary from time to time concerning 
the fate of the Vojvodina Hungarians are absolutely unfounded 
and unjustified. As a matter of fact, many people from Vojvodina 
fled because they were influenced by the propaganda that is 
disseminated in Hungary as well. 
  Jovanovich said that Yugoslav citizens could return home 
except those, of course, who had deserted because until they are 
granted amnesty, the latter are responsible for what they have 
done in the eye of the law. 
  The Yugoslav foreign minister said about the Democratic 
Community of Hungarians of Vojvodina that it was a recognized 
organization and the Yugoslav leaders would assess its operation 
positively as long as it functioned within a constitutional and 
legal framework. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

