<H3> <TI>   Koljevic: Geneva Talks `Step Closer to Peace' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901175694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1628 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1901175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Obrenovac, 19 Jan (TANJUG) -- Taking into 
consideration the intensive plenary and bilateral negotiations 
in Geneva, it could be said that we are a step closer to peace, 
particularly after the Serbian proposal to immediately establish 
peace and a modus vivendi, as well as solve other remaining 
political problems later, Serbian Vice President Nikola Koljevic 
told Radio Obrenovac today. 
  "Therefore, it is very important the three sides accept the 
establishment of peace and resolve the remaining disputes 
peacefully," Koljevic pointed out. 
  Koljevic said the joint declaration signed by the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia and the Republic of Croatia was "a 
significant step for overall Serb-Croat relations," stressing 
that progress was much slower in the negotiations with the 
Muslim side. [passage omitted] 

