<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Briquemont Accuses Croats of Blocking Convoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2001221194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2022 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2001221194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 20 (TANJUG) -- Commander of the United 
Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) for Bosnia-Herzegovina, Gen. 
Francis Briquemont, accused Thursday [20 January] Bosnian Croats 
of blocking the efforts to deliver humanitarian aid to Sarajevo 
by road. 
  Foreign news agencies reported Gen. Briquemont as saying in 
Sarajevo on Thursday that Bosnian Croats failed to keep their 
promise given on January 12 by their Commander, Ante Roso. They 
promised to enable UNPROFOR to repair the important Bjela 
bridge, near Jablanica, southern Bosnia-Herzegovina. The former 
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina has been ravaged by the 
civil war between local Moslems, Serbs and Croats for the past 
21 months. Gen. Briquemont said if the bridge was repaired this 
would facilitate the passage of humanitarian convoys from the 
Croat-controlled territories in western Bosnia through central 
Bosnia on their way to Sarajevo. The general said it was quite 
obvious that the Bosnian Croat Army (HVO) had no wish to help 
open the Mostar-Jablanica route. 
  Gen. Briquemont steps down as the U.N. forces commander for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina next week, after criticizing the U.N. policy 
in this former Yugoslav republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

