<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Skoda Representative Detained, Released in Iran </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1901162794 Prague CTK in English 0826 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1901162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, January 19 (CTK) -- A trade representative 
of the foreign sales company Skodaexport was imprisoned in Iran 
at the end of last year in as yet unclear circumstances, the 
independent daily MLADA FRONTA DNES reports today, citing 
"reliable sources." 
  The paper says its information has been confirmed by the 
head 
of Skodaexport's General Director's Office, Zdenek Sima, and 
Czech Foreign Ministry Spokesman Lucie Pilipova. The Iranian 
authorities imprisoned Vladislav Tyl for several days before 
releasing him. Now back in Prague, he declined to comment on 
his imprisonment. 
  Tyl was imprisoned just after a delegation left the country 
from the Skoda heavy engineering works based in Plzen, west 
Bohemia, which had been creating business contacts in Tehran. 
  Skoda Plzen Director General Lubomir Soudek told MLADA 
FRONTA 
DNES that he did not find out about Tyl's imprisonment until 
last week, and that he did not know the cause of his arrest. 
  Sima said that although the Iranians apologized to Tyl after 
releasing him, they did not explain why they had detained him. 
Sima does not know exactly who detained Tyl. "I do not know 
whether it was the secret service, counter-intelligence, or the 
criminal police. I don't think even Tyl knows," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

