<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Culture Minister Profiled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1901181894 Prague CTK in English 1416 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1901181894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 19 (CTK) -- Pavel Tigrid is to be new 
Czech culture minister to replace Jindrich Kabat, who resigned 
on Monday [17 January], Jan Kasal (KDU-CSL), deputy chairman of 
the Czech Parliament's Chamber of Deputies, told CTK today. 
Kabat is a KDU-CSL member while Tigrid is without party 
affiliation. 
  Tigrid, 77, lived in exile after the communist coup of 
February 1948. For 35 years he was editor-in-chief of the 
quarterly SVEDECTVI (TESTIMONY) published in Paris. After the 
fall of communism in Czechoslovakia in late 1989, he returned to 
Czechoslovakia and became adviser to Vaclav Havel, who was then 
Czechoslovak president. 

</TEXT>

