<H3> <TI>   National-Democratic Party To Join Rightist Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601182294 Warsaw PAP in English 1811 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 16 -- The National-Democratic Party 
(SN-D), headed by Jan Zamoyski, announced on Sunday its plan to 
join the agreement of four right-wing parties, the Real Politics 
Union (UPR), the Conservative Party (PK), Party of Christian 
Democrats (PCHD) and the Peasant-Christian Party (SLCH). 
  But UPR and SN-D leaders, attending a discussion on local 
governments on Sunday, said that they did not intend to form a 
national coalition in the forthcoming local elections. 
  Janusz Korwin Mikke, leader of the UPR, termed as 
"villainous" the recent proposal by the Social Democracy of the 
Republic of Poland (SDRP) to alter the local election law 
several months before expected elections. 
  According to Korwin Mikke, the idea of direct general 
elections for commune heads, town mayors and city presidents is 
an attempt to adjust the election law to the present situation. 

</TEXT>

