<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Returns `Extra' Centrel Energy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101173094 Paris AFP in English 1624 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, Jan 21 (AFP) -- Ukraine has apparently 
returned 200 million kilowatt-hours of energy it drew in extra 
imports from the joint Centrel electric system of eastern 
European countries, the Hungarian national electricity 
distribution centre said Friday [21 January]. 
  Over the past fortnight, the Centrel system maintained 
normal 
frequency levels after considerable fluctuation caused by 
unplanned Ukrainian imports since November, officials of the 
centre said. 
  The fluctuations caused slowdowns and overstrain with 
electric appliances, and Centrel countries -- the Czech 
republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Poland, Romania and the eastern 
part of Germany -- threatened Ukraine with separating it from 
the grid if it failed to return the energy drawn until Friday. 
  Ukraine was forced to import more energy than it had planned 
due to severe fuel shortages there. Hungary supplied a quarter 
of the extra energy drawn. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

