<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crude Oil Deliveries From Russia Resume </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101173194 Paris AFP in English 1622 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, Jan 21 (AFP) -- Russian crude deliveries 
to Hungary on the Friendship pipeline resumed Friday [21 
January] following a two-and-a-half day break since Tuesday, 
officials of the state-owned Hungarian Oil and Gas Company (MOL) 
said. The supply break was due to administrative problems at 
Nafta, the Russian exporter, MOL said. 
  The break, which "was not the first example of a halt of 
supplies", did not affect work at Hungary's oil refineries and 
resulted only in rescheduling a 40,000-ton delivery to Hungary, 
the officials said. Last year, Hungary imported 5.1 million 
tonnes of crude from Russia and this year's imports were also 
planned to exceed five million tons, they said. 

</TEXT>

