<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Recovery Program Scheduled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2301205894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2047 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2301205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 23 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslavia on Monday 
[24 January] launches a programme of economic recovery and 
reconstruction of the monetary system, Deputy Prime Minister 
Jovan Zebic said on Sunday. Zebic said the government on Sunday 
adopted the last in a series of measures necessary for launching 
the economic reform programme which would primarily focus on 
curbing hyperinflation. The programme for slashing the monster 
inflation whose monthly rate reached one million percent last 
December starts with the issuing of the new convertible dinar 
with 100-percent gold and hard currency backing. 
  Other measures include a radical reduction of the primary 
issue and an increase in production geared for the market made 
almost non-existent after many companies withdrew their products 
from the market because of hyperinflation. 
  Economic expert Dragoslav Avramovic, the chief architect of 
Yugoslavia's stabilization programme, said that the package did 
not envisage wage or price freezes and that the state could opt 
for such measures only in a very limited number of cases. 

</TEXT>

