<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Condemns Macedonian `Intolerance' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101153994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1418 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 21 Jan (TANJUG) -- The Federal Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs today expressed concern in connection with the 
recent arrest and expulsion of two priests of the Serbian 
Orthodox Church from the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia. 
The priests were accused of having "conducted religious rites 
in several villages in the municipality of Kumanovo without the 
permission of the Macedonian Orthodox Church and the Macedonian 
Ministry of Internal Affairs, and thus instigated national 
hatred and intolerance." 
  Recalling that this is not the first occasion on which the 
authorities of the former Yugoslav republic have shown 
intolerance toward the clergy of the Serbian Orthodox Church, 
the Yugoslav Ministry of Foreign Affairs stresses that by such 
behavior Skopje is depriving the Serbian people living in 
Macedonia of their religious rights. This is in contravention 
of international norms and documents that the Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia has accepted, the statement, which was 
forwarded to TANJUG today, goes on to say. 
  "This incites an atmosphere of insecurity and fear among the 
Serbs in Macedonia, whose status, despite the promises and 
alleged readiness of the relevant authorities, has not as yet 
been defined in the Constitution. In addition to the existing 
discrimination regarding the use of their mother tongue, 
employment, education, and information, this behaviour by the 
Macedonian authorities makes Serbs feel like second rate 
citizens," the statement says. 
  The Federal Ministry of Foreign Affairs expects the 
Macedonian side to take all necessary measures so that there 
should be no recurrence of such incidents. The ministry expects 
the Macedonian side to start resolving the issue of the 
constitutional status of the Serbian people living in Macedonia 
in the near future, in accordance with highest CSCE and UN 
standards. 

</TEXT>

