<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic, Opposition Discuss Unity Government </TI></H3>
<H4>   Djindic Meets With Milosevic </H4>
<F P=102> LD2101150794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1356 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 21 January (TANJUG) -- After talks with 
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic today, Zoran Djindjic, the 
main candidate of the Democratic Party (DS) and the president of 
the DS executive board, said that they had talked about a 
government of national unity. After nearly an hour of talks 
with the Serbian president, Djindjic said that no party could at 
this moment take the responsibility for forming the government, 
and particularly not, as he stressed, the party that had so far 
formed all Serbian governments. He said that they did not 
discuss the post of the prime minister, but added that it had 
been stressed during the talks that he had to be "a man of 
consensus." 
  The DS believes that the new government's program has to be 
different from all those we have had so far, Djindjic said. 
According to him, the Serbian president said that the future 
government's composition will not be determined by party 
allegiance. 
  Commenting on his impressions of the talks with the Serbian 
president, Djindjic emphasized that the government would be some 
kind of a government of national unity, which should have an 
all-party support and a nonpartisan program. 
  The DS stance is that the president of the new Serbian 
National Assembly should be an opposition deputy, and we hope 
that this will be the case, Djindjic said. He added that the 
president of Serbia "has a somewhat different opinion." 
According to Djindjic, the Serbian president said that the 
Socialist Party of Serbia, as the strongest party, had the right 
to the post of the president of the Serbian Assembly, while the 
opposition parties could have the posts of deputy presidents. 
The DS insists that "the parties [as received] have 
indisputable control of the finance, media, and internal 
affairs," Djindjic said. 
  "If we are not in the position to control for 24 hours a day 
the banks, state media, and the police, and in particular the 
struggle against crime, there is no point in talking about a new 
government and a new coalition," Djindjic stressed. Djindjic 
believes that the new government will not be formed in the next 
two weeks. 
  After Djindjic, Vuk Draskovic went in for talks with 
President Milosevic. Before that, he briefly said to reporters: 
"I have come to meet him and to talk." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50068 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu015_y_94006" </HT>


