<H3> <TI>   Albanians To Hold Assembly Session `Next Week' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101154494 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2101154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Milivoje Mihajlovic] </F>
  [Text] The Pristina-based newspaper ZERI writes that they 
have learned from sources close to Ibrahim Rugova that the first 
session of the republic of Kosovo's parliament will be held -- I 
quote -- somewhere in Pristina next week. ZERI also reports 
that the mandates of deputies, elected two years ago in the 
Albanian elections in Kosmet [Kosovo and Metohija], will be 
verified at the session. 
  In a statement for this paper, the Albanian politician Adem 
Demaci commented on this information and said that the Serbs 
have held 12 multiparty elections in the past 12 years [figures 
as received], while the Albanians went to the polls only once. 
Rexhep Qosja, the most influential Albanian intellectual, said 
that if Serbia allowed the session of the republic of Kosovo 
parliament to take place, this would confirm his earlier 
assessment that the organizers of the elections and the Albanian 
parliament were actually Quislings. Let me remind you that the 
first attempt to hold a session of the phantom republic of 
Kosovo's parliament in the Pristina-based Alaudin school 
[medresa Alaudin] was prevented by the police because there was 
a chance of this event provoking a rebellion of the Albanian 
separatists in Kosovo and Metohija. 

</TEXT>

