<H3> <TI>   Granic Sends Letter to UN on Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2101192694 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1800 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2101192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mate Granic, the Croatian deputy prime minister and 
foreign minister, said in his letter to UNSC [UN Security 
Council] Chairman Karel Kovanda that the joint declaration, 
signed by Croatia and the FRY in Geneva, was the first step 
forward in the process of the normalization of mutual relations. 
Granic also said that the government of the Republic of Croatia 
was deeply convinced that both sides will from now on act 
strictly in accordance with the provisions laid down by the 
Helsinki Final Document of 1975, and especially in line with the 
principle whereby international borders cannot and must not be 
changed by force. Granic stressed that the joint declaration 
was on no account directed against the third side [Muslims] and 
that it should ensure a modus vivendi for Croatian territories 
under UN protection, in keeping with the European Union plan and 
UNSC Resolution 871. 

</TEXT>

