<H3> <TI>   `Good' Turnout Reported at Krajina Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2301161594 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2301161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Miladin Manojlovic from Beli Manastir] </F>
  [Excerpts] As of 1300, 40 percent of the voters in 
Slavonija, Baranja, and Western Srem had visited the polling 
stations, which can be considered a good response considering 
the poor weather conditions in this area. 
  In the Beli Manastir electoral unit, as of 1300, 
approximately 40 percent of the voters have turned out. This 
percentage had already been achieved in Vukovar at 1200. The 
response will definitely be even greater since the sun is 
melting the ice and snow on the paths. The low temperatures and 
ice have forced many people to wait until this afternoon to 
vote. However, some just could not be dissuaded by the bad 
weather to fulfill their civic right and vote for one of the two 
presidential candidates in the republic of Serbian Krajina. 
[passage omitted] 
  The polling stations will remain open until 1900. The first 
unofficial results as to who has won the second round of 
elections, Milan Babic or Milan Martic, will be announced 
tomorrow evening after 1900. Vukovar has forwarded us the data 
for some other localities in the republic of Serbian Krajina. 
In Vojnic, 17 percent voted by noon; Vrgin Most 35 percent; 
Drnis 20 percent; Okucani 32 percent, Pakrac 50 percent; and 
Petrinja 30 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

